<Document>
<name>Grand Pacific Drive</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Grand Pacific Drive</h2><p><i>New South Wales, Australia · Royal NP to Kiama via Sea Cliff Bridge</i></p><p><b>140 km of escarpment coast just south of Sydney — the Sea Cliff Bridge is one of Australia's signature road photographs.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>86 km (53 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs no stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Year-round; whale-watching May–November</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Weekend traffic from Sydney, motorcyclists, narrow lanes through coastal villages, fog on the escarpment</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>128</td></tr></table><hr><p>Sydney's best escape drive. The road crosses Royal National Park at Bald Hill (the country's third-oldest national park, 1879), then drops down to the Illawarra coast where the original road kept being closed by rockfalls from the cliffs above. The 2005 Sea Cliff Bridge was the engineering answer — a 665 m elevated deck cantilevered over the surf, attached to the cliff at one end. From Stanwell Park southward you pass an unbroken chain of surf beaches and a famous string of fish-and-chip shops, ending at Kiama where the ocean fires through a basalt blowhole on a strong southerly. Continue south through Berry to Jervis Bay for some of the whitest sand in Australia.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Bald Hill</b> — Headland lookout over the entire Illawarra coast — Lawrence Hargrave's 1894 hang-gliding experiments here are commemorated by a memorial. Paragliders launch on clear afternoons.</li><li><b>Sea Cliff Bridge</b> — 665 m of road suspended over the surf below cliffs that wouldn't stop falling. Pedestrian walkway on the seaward side; pull off in the small parking pocket on the south end.</li><li><b>Wollongong / Flagstaff Hill</b> — Coastal industrial city with a surprisingly photogenic 1872 lighthouse on a basalt headland. Nan Tien Buddhist temple, the largest in the southern hemisphere, is a short detour west.</li><li><b>Kiama Blowhole</b> — Sea spray fired up to 25 m through a basalt sea cave on a southeasterly swell. The lookout is right in town. Smaller but more reliable Little Blowhole 1 km south.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
